  <a href="#1" id="1">
   An intestinal operation to lower the cholesterol of heart attack patients reduced their risk for another heart attack or death from heart disease, researchers said today.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   Dr. Henry Buchwald of the University of Minnesota, who directed the study, said the surgery should be considered along with cholesterol-lowering drugs as a possible standard treatment.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   "It has a role in the management of patients with high cholesterol who have had a heart attack," Buchwald said.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   "It is eminently logical to extend all cholesterol-lowering therapy, including this, to patients with high cholesterol who have not had a heart attack".
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   The overall risk of dying from heart disease or suffering another non-fatal heart attack was reduced 35 percent among the surgical patients with the healthiest hearts.
  </a>
